#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:335
msgid "Argout Arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:337
msgid ""
"Argout arrays are arrays that appear in the input arguments in C, but are in "
"fact output arrays.  This pattern occurs often when there is more than one "
"output variable and the single return argument is therefore not sufficient.  "
"In Python, the conventional way to return multiple arguments is to pack them "
"into a sequence (tuple, list, etc.) and return the sequence.  This is what "
"the argout typemaps do.  If a wrapped function that uses these argout "
"typemaps has more than one return argument, they are packed into a tuple or "
"list, depending on the version of Python.  The Python user does not pass "
"these arrays in, they simply get returned.  For the case where a dimension "
"is specified, the python user must provide that dimension as an argument.  "
"The argout signatures are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:352
msgid "``(   DATA_TYPE ARGOUT_ARRAY1[ANY] )``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:353
msgid "``(   DATA_TYPE* ARGOUT_ARRAY1, int DIM1 )``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:354
msgid "``(   int DIM1, DATA_TYPE* ARGOUT_ARRAY1 )``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:358
msgid "``(   DATA_TYPE ARGOUT_ARRAY2[ANY][ANY] )``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:362
msgid "``(   DATA_TYPE ARGOUT_ARRAY3[ANY][ANY][ANY] )``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:366
msgid "``(   DATA_TYPE ARGOUT_ARRAY4[ANY][ANY][ANY][ANY] )``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:368
msgid ""
"These are typically used in situations where in C/C++, you would allocate "
"a(n) array(s) on the heap, and call the function to fill the array(s) "
"values.  In Python, the arrays are allocated for you and returned as new "
"array objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:373
msgid ""
"Note that we support ``DATA_TYPE*`` argout typemaps in 1D, but not 2D or "
"3D.  This is because of a quirk with the `SWIG`_ typemap syntax and cannot "
"be avoided.  Note that for these types of 1D typemaps, the Python function "
"will take a single argument representing ``DIM1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:379
msgid "Argout View Arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:381
msgid ""
"Argoutview arrays are for when your C code provides you with a view of its "
"internal data and does not require any memory to be allocated by the user.  "
"This can be dangerous.  There is almost no way to guarantee that the "
"internal data from the C code will remain in existence for the entire "
"lifetime of the NumPy array that encapsulates it.  If the user destroys the "
"object that provides the view of the data before destroying the NumPy array, "
"then using that array may result in bad memory references or segmentation "
"faults.  Nevertheless, there are situations, working with large data sets, "
"where you simply have no other choice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/swig.interface-file.rst:392
msgid ""
"The C code to be wrapped for argoutview arrays are characterized by "
"pointers: pointers to the dimensions and double pointers to the data, so "
"that these values can be passed back to the user.  The argoutview typemap "
"signatures are therefore"
msgstr ""

